\begin{abstract}
Hallucination is usually evaluated as a binary defect: a statement is supported or it is not.
This misses a central property of language use: the same unsupported content can be dangerous in a medical answer, harmless in a metaphor, and useful in fiction or ideation.
We argue that hallucination should instead be evaluated relative to the prompt's \emph{truth regime}, $\TR(p)=(O,\sigma,\kappa)$: the oracle $O$ that grounds truth, the stylistic latitude $\sigma$ that permits surface variation, and the invention license $\kappa$ that determines whether new truth-conditional content may be introduced.
Under this view, \Hallu\ is a truth-regime violation, while \PD\ is licensed and useful divergence.
As empirical motivation, we run a strict-regime diagnostic study (12{,}469 texts, 10 models, 310K claims) using a HalluLens-style binary verifier.
Even when factual invention is never licensed, creative intent raises measured hallucination (+12.8~\%), writing format has the strongest effect (+21.4~\%), and format-specific factual norms moderate the creativity effect.
These patterns do not constitute a complete \TR-aware evaluator; they show why one is needed: current binary pipelines are technically mature, but conceptually under-specified with respect to the prompt contract.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction: The Creativity-Hallucination Paradox}\label{sec:intro}

% === CLAIMS SUPPORTED HERE ===
% Claim 1 (motivation), Claim 2 (SOTA gap), Claim 5 (normative preview)

Large language models (LLMs) sometimes state things that are not true.
The community calls these errors \emph{hallucinations}: the model produces fluent, confident text that is not supported by evidence or contradicts known facts \citep{ji_survey_2023, huang_survey_2025}.
Hallucination is widely regarded as the central reliability barrier for deploying LLMs in high-stakes settings such as medicine, law, and education \citep{lin_truthfulqa_2022}.
Consequently, a large body of work aims to detect, measure, and reduce hallucination \citep{li_halueval_2023, wei_measuring_2024, thorne_fever_2018, chen_menli_2023}.

Yet there is a paradox.
When users ask an LLM to write fiction, brainstorm, or propose creative solutions, they actively \emph{want} the model to go beyond established facts.
In these settings, punishing every unsupported statement would suppress the very outputs users seek \citep{franceschelli_creativity_2024, hou_creativityprism_2025, rick_supermind_2023}.
A brainstorming tool that only mentions ideas that already exist is useless; a medical assistant that invents diagnoses is dangerous.
The difference is not in the text itself, but in \emph{what the prompt asked for}.

\paragraph{The diagnostic gap.}
Current evaluation frameworks do not account for this difference.
On one side, hallucination benchmarks treat any unsupported content as a defect and seek to minimize it \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}.
On the other side, creativity benchmarks treat novelty as a virtue and seek to maximize it, often without checking factual grounding \citep{hou_creativityprism_2025, franceschelli_creativity_2024, acar_creativity_2019}.
Neither tradition conditions its scores on what the user's prompt actually authorizes.
As a result, the same output can be scored as a serious failure by one framework and a creative success by another, depending on which evaluation protocol is applied, not on whether the divergence was appropriate given the user's intent.
We examine both traditions and their shared blind spot in Section~\ref{sec:sota}.

Recent theoretical work shows that LLMs cannot avoid hallucination entirely: formal proofs via incompleteness and undecidability \citep{banerjee_llms_2024} and calibration arguments \citep{kalai_why_nodate} establish a nonzero \emph{structural} error floor.
Yet the same mechanism also produces novel hypotheses and creative combinations that users request in open-ended tasks \citep{sun_hallucinating_2024, he_shakespearean_2025, sui_confabulation_2024}.
In Section~\ref{sec:inherent}, we argue that the goal should be to \emph{control} divergence relative to the task's \emph{truth regime} (\TR), not to eliminate it.

\paragraph{Our thesis.}
We claim that hallucination is not a binary property of text.
It is \emph{relative to the prompt's truth regime} (\TR): the task-specific contract that specifies what must be true, what may be uncertain, and what may be invented.
Under a strict \TR\ (e.g., ``summarize this document accurately''), any unsupported claim is a hallucination (\Hallu).
Under a permissive \TR\ (e.g., ``write a fiction''), that same divergence may instead constitute \emph{productive divergence} (\PD): a regime-compliant departure from established facts that is novel and task-useful, and therefore fulfills rather than violates the user's creative intent (\CI).
The distinction is not about the text itself, but it is about whether the prompt authorized the deviation.
Evaluation that ignores this conflates \Hallu\ with \PD.

\paragraph{Empirical motivation.}
We use the empirical study in this paper as a diagnostic stress test, not as a complete implementation of \TR-aware evaluation.
We generate 12{,}469 texts from 10~LLMs under a strict \TR\ where factual content invention is not licensed, decompose each text into atomic claims, and check those claims against Wikipedia with a HalluLens-style binary verifier \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}.
The study asks whether a strong current verifier remains stable when prompt style and format vary while $\kappa$ is held low.
It does not test the full \Hallu/\PD\ relabeling problem under permissive regimes; rather, it shows that even under a fixed strict regime, measured hallucination is substantially conditioned by prompt-level signals.
Three findings follow: (i)~higher \CI\ raises measured hallucination by 12.8~\%; (ii)~writing format is the largest single driver (+21~\%); and (iii)~format-specific factual constraints moderate how much creativity raises hallucination.
\noindent\textbf{This paper makes three contributions.}
\emph{First} (conceptual), we introduce $\TR(p)=(O,\sigma,\kappa)$ and a minimal vocabulary (\TR, \CI, \PD, \Hallu) for making the prompt contract explicit (Section~\ref{sec:framework}).
\emph{Second} (diagnostic), we show that hallucination and creativity evaluation share a blind spot: neither tradition explicitly conditions its scores on what the prompt authorizes (Section~\ref{sec:sota}).
\emph{Third} (empirical), we use a strict-regime stress test to show that HalluLens-style binary verification is prompt-sensitive even when invention is disallowed (Section~\ref{sec:method-results}).
\emph{Fourth} (programmatic), we outline a research agenda for \TR-aware benchmarks that score \Hallu\ and \PD\ separately under explicit oracle and permission annotations (Section~\ref{sec:agenda}).



\section{Terminology and Conceptual Framework}\label{sec:framework}

% === CLAIMS SUPPORTED HERE ===
% Claim 2 (diagnostic: intent-agnostic evaluation conflates harmful hallucination and productive divergence)
% Claim 5 (normative: hallucination is TR-relative; not an absolute property of text)
% Claim 6 (setup: TR/CI-aware evaluation must separate PD from H and judge excess vs licensed deviation)

\paragraph{Motivation.}
The literature uses the word \emph{hallucination} broadly, but not consistently.
Surveys commonly group together factuality errors against world knowledge and faithfulness errors against a provided source, sometimes adding axes such as intrinsic vs.\ extrinsic causes and different granularities~\cite{ji_survey_2023, huang_survey_2025, zhang_sirens_nodate}.
Benchmarking work further argues that hallucination is often conflated with factuality and that evaluation depends on the chosen oracle and evaluator reliability \cite{bang_hallulens_2025}.
To study creativity-hallucination tradeoffs, we fix a minimal vocabulary that makes the \emph{prompt contract} explicit.
Throughout, we distinguish \emph{prompt-level} variables (what the user requests) from \emph{output-level} properties (what the model produces), and adopt a \emph{claim-level} unit of analysis because evaluations explicitly vary by granularity.


\textbf{Creative intent (\CI; prompt-level).}
The extent to which the user \emph{requests novelty} in the response (e.g., alternatives, analogies, imaginative options) \emph{under stated constraints}.
\CI\ increases the preferred exploration of the solution space; creativity is usually defined as \emph{novel and useful/appropriate} relative to given constraints. \cite{runco_standard_2012, acar_creativity_2019, franceschelli_creativity_2024}.

\textbf{Truth regime (\TR; prompt-level contract).}
A task-specific contract that determines (i) what must be \emph{grounded/true}, (ii) what may be \emph{uncertain} (but should be labeled), and (iii) what may be \emph{invented}, together with the relevant \emph{oracle} (source document, retrieval set, database, world facts).
\TR\ is necessary because “hallucination” definitions and evaluation oracles vary across settings \cite{bang_hallulens_2025}.
Critically, we separate two independent permissions within a regime: \emph{stylistic latitude} ($\sigma$), how freely form may vary while preserving propositions \cite{jin_deep_2022} and \emph{factual content invention} ($\kappa$), whether new factual content may be introduced.
Many real prompts request creative style without factual content invention (e.g., ``explain photosynthesis like a poet''); here $\sigma$ is high but $\kappa$ remains low, so figurative language is welcome but fabricated claims are not \cite{franceschelli_creativity_2024}.


\textbf{Faithfulness (\Faith; output-level).}
Whether the output \emph{adheres to the prompt} and is \emph{supported by the provided evidence} (documents, retrieved passages, tables), without introducing unsupported details.
This is the central failure mode in grounded generation and summarization, where fluent outputs can exceed source support~\cite{maynez_faithfulness_2020, kryscinski_evaluating_2020, huang_survey_2025, malin_review_2025}.

\textbf{Accuracy / factuality (\Acc; output-level).}
Whether the claims that must be true under \TR\ are actually supported by an appropriate external source (e.g., references, gold labels, or world knowledge).
This corresponds to QA and fact-checking evaluation.

\textbf{Hallucination (\Hallu; claim-level).}
As we define, a hallucination is a \TR-violation. The model presents a claim \emph{as grounded/true} where \TR\ requires truth or evidence, but the claim is unsupported (\Faith) and/or incorrect (\Acc).
This definition unifies faithfulness and factuality failures while making the oracle explicit~\cite{maynez_faithfulness_2020, bang_hallulens_2025}.


\textbf{Productive divergence (\PD; claim-level).}
Content that would count as hallucination under a strict factual standard, but is allowed by the prompt's truth regime and helps accomplish the task.
Formally, \PD\ is a \TR-compliant exploration that proposes \emph{novel} candidates (hypotheses, alternatives, analogies, fictional details) where \TR\ permits speculation or invention; it is \emph{productive} when the deviation is useful and appropriate under task constraints---the standard creativity criterion \cite{diedrich_are_2015, acar_creativity_2019}.
This framing echoes non-LLM uses of ``productive divergence'' as variation that energizes performance \cite{parry_team_2023, lingard_pulling_2017}.
Crucially, if \TR\ demands grounding, the same deviation is \Hallu, not \PD.


\noindent\textbf{Decision rule (simple and testable).}
Given prompt $p$ and output $y$ and an oracle $O$: specify $\TR(p)$, decompose $y$ into atomic claims, then label each claim using $O$ as \Hallu\ (truth-conditional under $\TR$ but unsupported/incorrect), \PD\ (licensed by $\TR$ and task-useful), or neither (stylistic variation, benign noise), see Appendix~\ref{app:decision-rule} for the step-by-step procedure.

\paragraph{Worked example.}
Consider the prompt ``Explain photosynthesis in a poetic style, but keep the science accurate.''
Here, the oracle is scientific world knowledge, $\sigma$ is high because figurative language is requested, and $\kappa$ remains low because the science must stay accurate.
Calling chlorophyll ``a green workshop for sunlight'' is stylistic variation, but claiming that plants make sugar from moonlight is \Hallu.
If the prompt instead asks for a fictional plant ecology where moonlight powers growth, the same moonlight claim can be \PD\ if it is useful, clearly framed as invented, and consistent with the fictional constraints.




\noindent Under this vocabulary, we do not oppose ``creativity vs.\ truth''.
We oppose \textbf{\Hallu} (\TR\ violations) to \textbf{\PD} (\TR-compliant creativity). Intent-agnostic factuality evaluation fails to separate these two outcomes.



