\subsection{Truth Regimes and Regime-Relative Divergence}\label{sec:truth-regimes}

The terms above give us a vocabulary for individual claims; we still need a way to specify \emph{what the task allows}.
We formalize this as $\TR(p)=(O,\sigma,\kappa)$: an oracle $O$ (the reference against which claims are checked), a stylistic latitude $\sigma$, and an invention license $\kappa$ \cite{ji_survey_2023,huang_survey_2025}.
Table~\ref{tab:canonical-truth-regimes} instantiates three canonical regimes.
Existing benchmarks typically fix $O$ but rarely annotate $(\sigma,\kappa)$ explicitly, making it easy to conflate \PD{} with \Hallu{} \cite{bang_hallulens_2025,jiang_survey_2024}.

\paragraph{Claim-level labeling.}
Given a regime $\TR(p)$, each atomic claim falls into one of the categories already defined: \emph{stylistic variation} (form changes, no new propositions), \PD\ (novel content licensed by $\kappa$ and task-useful), \Hallu\ (truth-conditional content unsupported by oracle $O$), or \emph{benign noise} (minor inaccuracies with negligible impact) \cite{ji_survey_2023,huang_survey_2025,bang_hallulens_2025}.

\noindent\textbf{Two-sided failure relative to $\kappa$.}
When $\kappa$ is low, excess deviation increases \Hallu; when $\kappa$ is high, \emph{insufficient} deviation yields conservative outputs that fail the creative objective, a failure mode captured by creativity benchmarks but not by hallucination-only scoring \cite{hou_creativityprism_2025}.
Our study varies \emph{only} $\sigma$ (style) while keeping $\kappa$ minimal; therefore, any increase in factual deviation remains \Hallu\ under the tested regime.

With this vocabulary and labeling procedure in place, the natural question is: do existing evaluation frameworks already capture the \TR/\CI\ distinction? The next section examines both hallucination and creativity benchmarks and shows that they do not.

\section{Evaluation Landscape and the Case for Controlled Divergence}\label{sec:sota}\label{sec:inherent}

\paragraph{Two traditions, one shared blind spot.}
Hallucination benchmarks treat divergence from an oracle as a defect to minimize \citep{ji_survey_2023,huang_survey_2025,bang_hallulens_2025}; creativity benchmarks treat it as evidence of novelty to maximize \citep{hou_creativityprism_2025}.
This division holds for single-intent tasks but breaks down for mixed-intent prompts that combine novelty with factual constraints \citep{wang_user-centric_2024}: the same surface deviation can be \PD\ or \Hallu, yet on both sides the prompt contract $(O,\sigma,\kappa)$ remains implicit.
Hallucination pipelines assume $\kappa$ is low; creativity pipelines score novelty without specifying which claims are bound to an oracle, making it easy to conflate regime-compliant exploration with genuine \TR-violations.

\subsection{Hallucination evaluation: factuality, faithfulness, and reasoning validity}
Hallucination evaluation is anchored in the choice of an oracle, either \emph{world knowledge} (\Acc: factuality) or \emph{provided context} (\Faith: faithfulness) \citep{ji_survey_2023, huang_survey_2025}, with additional axes such as contradiction vs.\ fabrication, intrinsic vs.\ extrinsic errors \citep{zhang_sirens_nodate}, and evaluation granularity (token/span/claim/output) \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}.
Accordingly, modern protocols increasingly rely on claim-level decomposition and automated or semi-automated verification, e.g., retrieval+Natural Language Inference (NLI) \citep{chen_menli_2023, hughes_vectara_2023} or QA-based checking \citep{wang_asking_2020}, building on fact-checking \citep{thorne_fever_2018} and truthfulness benchmarks \citep{lin_truthfulqa_2022, li_halueval_2023}.
A key methodological motivation is diagnosticity: explicit claims make oracle comparison and error typing more interpretable than output-level judgments \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}.

However, these axes are necessary but not sufficient for \TR/\CI-aware judgment.
Most hallucination pipelines implicitly assume a strict invention license ($\kappa$ low): any unsupported truth-conditional content is treated as a failure.
In grounded generation, this assumption is defensible, but it collapses when prompts license speculation or invention.
Even in summarization, a statement can be factually correct (\Acc\ satisfied) yet unsupported by the source (\Faith\ violated), showing that \Hallu\ depends on the oracle and \TR, not on the text alone \citep{maynez_faithfulness_2020, kryscinski_evaluating_2020}.
Without explicit $(O,\sigma,\kappa)$ metadata, the same verification pipeline can conflate stylistic variation, factual content invention, and regime violations.

\subsection{Creativity evaluation: fragmented metrics and evaluator dependence}
Creativity is commonly defined as combining \emph{novelty} with \emph{value/appropriateness} under constraints \citep{runco_standard_2012}, but operationalizations and scoring procedures vary sharply across tasks and domains \citep{acar_creativity_2019, diedrich_are_2015, franceschelli_creativity_2024, ismayilzada_creativity_2025}.
Recent LLM work therefore treats creativity as multi-dimensional and task-dependent, with benchmarks spanning (i)~divergent-thinking tests and Torrance Tests of Creative Thinking (TTCT) like rubrics \citep{organisciak_beyond_2023, nguyen_divergent-convergent_2025, dinu_integrated_2024, zhao_assessing_nodate, he_what_2025}, (ii)~creative-writing evaluation (rubric- and reference-based) \citep{fein_litbench_2025, ippolito_creative_2022, ismayilzada_evaluating_2025, li_cr-llm_2024, li_automated_2025, delorenzo_creativeval_2024, wang_f2rl_2024}, and (iii)~constrained creativity in code/math and interactive problem solving \citep{lu_benchmarking_2025, ye_assessing_2024, qian_escapebench_2025, tian_macgyver_2025, hou_creativityprism_2025}.
\textsc{CreativityPrism} exemplifies this trend by aligning heterogeneous tasks to shared dimensions (quality, novelty, diversity) \citep{hou_creativityprism_2025} while retaining task-local scoring rules (rubric-based criteria, dispersion/diversity signals, and constrained correctness--novelty trade-offs) \citep{lu_benchmarking_2025, ye_assessing_2024, lu_ai_2025}.

Creativity judgments also remain evaluator-dependent: ratings shift with rubric design \citep{shively_measuring_2018, dietz_principles_2025, marco_reader_2025}, rater backgrounds \citep{cyriac_metrics_2025, ismayilzada_evaluating_2025, jr_how_2025}, and reader profiles \citep{ippolito_creative_2022}, changing model rankings even under identical prompts when using LLM-as-judge protocols \citep{liu_g-eval_2023, zheng_judging_2023, li_llms_2025, han_judges_2025}.

From a \TR/\CI\ perspective, however, the deeper issue is that creativity benchmarks rarely treat the truth regime as an explicit variable.
Novelty signals may be rewarded without distinguishing \PD\ from \Hallu\ \citep{sui_confabulation_2024, padmakumar_measuring_2025}, even when factual grounding is part of the prompt contract \citep{wang_user-centric_2024, bang_hallulens_2025}.
Existing faithfulness metrics \citep{maynez_faithfulness_2020, pagnoni_understanding_2021, kryscinski_evaluating_2020} and semantic verification tools \citep{wang_asking_2020, aynetdinov_semscore_2024, chen_menli_2023} could detect such violations, but they are not integrated into creativity evaluation pipelines.
This omission, shared with hallucination benchmarks, produces a concrete failure mode.

\subsection{Failure mode: \CI-agnostic evaluation conflates \PD\ with \Hallu}
When $\TR$ is left implicit, two symmetric errors arise: creativity benchmarks \citep{hou_creativityprism_2025, fein_litbench_2025} assume multiple valid outputs without conditioning on an external oracle, while hallucination benchmarks \citep{bang_hallulens_2025, lin_truthfulqa_2022} treat unsupported claims as errors relative to a specified oracle.
Under a permissive regime ($\kappa$ high), strict factuality checks or semantic verification misclassify licensed speculation as \Hallu\ (false positives on \PD), an issue documented for both human \citep{cyriac_metrics_2025} and automated raters \citep{sui_confabulation_2024}.
Under a strict regime ($\kappa$ low), novelty-oriented scores \citep{liu_g-eval_2023, zheng_judging_2023} reward confident fabrications that boost apparent originality (false negatives on \Hallu) \citep{chen_menli_2023, dietz_principles_2025, li_llms_2025}.
Even benchmarks with domain-specific correctness constraints \citep{lu_benchmarking_2025, ye_assessing_2024, hou_creativityprism_2025, delorenzo_creativeval_2024} underspecify the prompt-level contract as a general variable, motivating a minimal evaluation layer that makes $(O,\sigma,\kappa)$ explicit \citep{wang_user-centric_2024, boubdir_elo_nodate}.

Beyond evaluation gaps, there is a deeper reason why the \PD/\Hallu\ confusion persists: hallucination cannot simply be engineered away.

\subsection{Why universal suppression of H is neither feasible nor desirable}
LLMs are probabilistic next-token predictors trained under incomplete supervision; they produce plausible continuations even when the truth is underspecified, so eliminating \Hallu\ universally would require restricting the model or the task class.
Formal arguments support this claim \citep{banerjee_llms_2024,cossio_comprehensive_2025}, and empirical evidence confirms that even strict \TRs\ reveal large residual error rates on short-form QA \citep{mallen_when_2023,cheng_evaluating_2023,gruber_complextempqa100m_2025}, truthfulness benchmarks \citep{lin_truthfulqa_2022,wei_measuring_2024}, and domain-specific evaluations \citep{rahman_defan_2024,sadat_mscinli_2024,uluoglakci_hypotermqa_2024}.
HalluLens confirms that \Hallu\ and \Acc\ are distinct constructs, making the relevant floor inherently \TR-dependent \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}.

Yet the same generative mechanism that produces unsupported claims also produces the novel hypotheses and creative combinations that users request in open-ended tasks.
Several systems exploit this deliberately through a \emph{diverge-then-converge} pattern: first induce diverse candidates, then filter or verify to meet the task's \TR.
\citet{sun_hallucinating_2024} formalize ``good hallucinations'' as reasoning paths that remain correct after convergence; \citet{banerjee_does_2025} show that verification-style mitigation can preserve divergent thinking whereas certain decoding interventions suppress it.
Concrete instantiations, including creative problem-solving scaffolds \citep{rick_supermind_2023}, intent-hypothesis grounding \citep{bodonhelyi_user_2024}, logic-to-language transfer \citep{you_mih-tcct_2025}, and style and correct fine-tuning \citep{roychowdhury_fistech_2024}. All treat divergence as a resource controlled by a subsequent convergence step, not a defect.

Since \Hallu\ has a structural floor and the same divergence drives \PD, the practical goal cannot be universal suppression of \Hallu{} but \TR-calibrated control: specify the regime upfront, enable divergence where \CI\ warrants it, and enforce convergence before any output is presented as fact.
This perspective aligns with evidence that divergence improves outputs valued in creative contexts (\PD\ under permissive \TR) yet becomes \Hallu\ under strict regimes \citep{sui_confabulation_2024,he_shakespearean_2025}. Operationally, such control can take the form of explicit mode signaling (hypothesis vs.\ claim), selective abstention, multi-sample generation with verification, or human-in-the-loop selection when automated judges are brittle \citep{bang_hallulens_2025,li_llms_2025}.


\section{Diagnostic Evidence: Binary Verification Under a Strict Truth Regime}\label{sec:method-results}
% === CLAIMS SUPPORTED HERE ===
% C1 (empirical signal), C2 (manipulation check), supports C6 feasibility

The preceding sections argue that current evaluation pipelines are conceptually under-specified because they score unsupported content without representing the prompt's truth regime.
We therefore use the experiment as a diagnostic stress test of a strong binary verifier under a deliberately strict regime.
The question is not whether the pipeline already separates \Hallu\ from \PD; it does not.
The question is whether increasing stylistic \CI\ and changing writing format, while holding factual content invention disallowed ($\kappa$ low), changes measured claim-level \Hallu.
The verification pipeline follows HalluLens \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}, which advocates separating \Hallu\ from \Acc\ and evaluating at the claim level for diagnosticity.
Concretely, all three task types share the same $\TR$: the prompt requests content grounded in Wikipedia knowledge ($O = $ world knowledge), allows stylistic variation ($\sigma \in \{\text{low}, \text{moderate}, \text{high}\}$) but does \emph{not} license factual content invention ($\kappa = $ low); any unsupported truth-conditional claim therefore counts as \Hallu.


