\paragraph{Writing format is the single largest driver.}
The requested format dominates all other factors: \textsc{lesson\_plan} produces 21\% more hallucination than \textsc{interview} ($\rho = 0.45$), as visible in Figure~\ref{fig:creativity-effect} where the middle panel sits consistently above the other two regardless of creativity level or model.

\paragraph{Creative intent raises hallucination monotonically.}
Without permission to invent facts, moving from \textsc{factual} to \textsc{very\_creative} raises hallucination by $+12.8$\% (Table~\ref{tab:key-findings}); every line in Figure~\ref{fig:creativity-effect} slopes upward across all three tasks.
A mediation analysis supports the interpretation that this pattern is not merely an artifact of longer or more claim-dense outputs.
On a subset scored with CreativityPrism \citep{hou_creativityprism_2025} ($N{=}8{,}376$), divergent-thinking and writing-quality scores rise alongside hallucination, consistent with an empirical coupling between creative prompting and measured unsupportedness even under a regime that never licenses invention (full correlation matrices and claim-level distributions in Appendix~\ref{app:stats}).

\paragraph{Factual constraints moderate the creativity effect.}
The task$\times$creativity interaction reveals a key asymmetry.
\textsc{lesson\_plan} and \textsc{interview} show comparable creativity slopes ($+10.6$ and $+14.3$\% swings respectively), differing only in baseline level.
By contrast, \textsc{news\_article} shows a significantly dampened slope ($+8.4$\%, interaction OR~$= 0.77$, $p_{\text{FDR}} < 10^{-77}$): journalism's implicit factual norms constrain how much creative prompting inflates hallucination.
This is visible in Figure~\ref{fig:creativity-effect}, where \textsc{news\_article} slopes (right panel) are systematically flatter than those in \textsc{interview} (left panel).
The same creative instruction thus produces markedly different binary-verification outcomes depending on the format's factual expectations, evidence that measured hallucination is conditioned by prompt format and creative intent even under a fixed strict regime.

