Target output length has a significant but weaker effect ($\rho = 0.11$, $p < 10^{-32}$), roughly one-quarter the magnitude of the task effect; per-model profiles for all three tasks are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:length-effect} (Appendix~\ref{app:length-effect}).

\subsection{Evaluator Reliability}

Since our pipeline uses LLMs to judge hallucination, a natural concern is evaluator dependence \citep{bang_hallulens_2025,dietz_principles_2025,zheng_judging_2023}.
We replicated the full pipeline with four judges (mimo-v2-flash (primary)~\cite{xiaomi2026mimov2flash}, deepseek-v3.2 \cite{deepseek2025v32}, llama-3.3-70b-instruct \cite{meta2024llama33}, and qwen3.5-397b-a17b \cite{alibaba2025qwen3}) on 90~shared prompts.
All six evaluator pairs reach substantial agreement (mean $\kappa_{\mathrm{agree}} = 0.756$, mean agreement~$= 88.1\%$; Table~\ref{tab:pairwise} in Appendix~\ref{app:evaluator}).
Absolute hallucination rates shift by at most 6.4~\% across judges, but the \emph{relative ordering} of every experimental condition is preserved (Table~\ref{tab:evaluator-rates}).
Thus, our conclusions are robust to evaluator choice.

\section{Research Agenda (Open Problems)}\label{sec:agenda}

% === CLAIMS SUPPORTED HERE ===
% Operationalizes Claim 6 and extends Claims 3--5 into future work.

The framework and findings above motivate six open problems, organized from measurement foundations (items~1--3) to system-level design (items~4--6).


\textbf{Operationalizing \CI\ and \TR\ as scorable variables.}
Our study operationalizes creative intent as a three-level categorical variable and truth regime as a fixed contract.
For general-purpose evaluation, both constructs need finer-grained operationalizations.
\CI\ could be placed on a continuous scale via pairwise preference judgments fitted to a Bradley--Terry or Elo model, analogously to how arena-style leaderboards score overall quality \citep{boubdir_elo_nodate}.
\TR\ could be decomposed into its three components $(O, \sigma, \kappa)$ and each annotated independently, making regime boundaries explicit rather than implicit in the task label.
A key challenge is inter-annotator reliability: creativity judgments are notoriously evaluator-dependent \citep{acar_creativity_2019, marco_reader_2025, ismayilzada_evaluating_2025}, and regime boundaries involve normative choices (what \emph{should} be grounded?) that require domain expertise.

\textbf{Automatic \TR\ inference from prompts.}
Users rarely specify a formal truth regime, so intent classifiers must infer $\TR(p)$ from prompt text \citep{wang_user-centric_2024, bodonhelyi_user_2024}.
Calibration is critical: misclassifying a strict-\TR\ prompt as permissive suppresses warranted penalties, while the reverse penalizes legitimate \PD.
Hybrid approaches (classifier-based defaults with user override) and failure-mode analysis on ambiguous prompts deserve investigation.

\textbf{Metrics for ``excessive'' \Hallu\ under a given \TR.}
Current metrics treat hallucination rate as a single number.
Under a \TR-aware framework, what matters is \emph{excess} deviation relative to the regime's tolerance.
This requires (i)~severity weighting (a fabricated safety claim is worse than a minor date error), (ii)~claim-level vs.\ output-level aggregation (a single critical hallucination may outweigh many benign ones), and (iii)~regime-conditioned baselines (the ``acceptable'' rate differs between grounded summarization and brainstorming).
Existing severity-aware proposals in hallucination evaluation \citep{bang_hallulens_2025, huang_survey_2025} and risk-weighted approaches in factuality benchmarks \citep{wei_measuring_2024, lin_truthfulqa_2022} provide starting points, but none currently conditions severity on an explicit \TR\ contract.

\textbf{Robust \Hallu\ detection under stylistic variation.}
Because stylistic creativity alone raises measured hallucination, NLI-based verifiers \citep{aynetdinov_semscore_2024, chen_menli_2023} may conflate figurative language with unsupported claims.
A dedicated suite pairing identical factual content with varying stylistic treatments would isolate verifier brittleness from genuine divergence \citep{jin_deep_2022}.

\textbf{Controlling \Hallu\ without collapsing \PD.}
Mitigation techniques (constrained decoding, retrieval augmentation, post-hoc verification) typically target \Hallu\ reduction without measuring the collateral effect on creative quality.
Recent work shows these trade-offs are asymmetric: verification style interventions can preserve divergent thinking, while decoding constraints may suppress it \citep{banerjee_does_2025, he_shakespearean_2025, sun_hallucinating_2024, li_jointly_nodate}.
\TR-aware evaluation should therefore report \emph{both} \Hallu\ reduction and \PD\ preservation under the same regime.

\textbf{Benchmarks crossing task $\times$ \CI $\times$ \TR.}
No existing benchmark systematically crosses task type, creative intent level, and truth regime as independent variables.
Such a benchmark needs a task gradient (summarization $\rightarrow$ style transfer $\rightarrow$ fiction), multi-level \CI\ manipulations, explicit $(O,\sigma,\kappa)$ annotations, and protocols scoring \Hallu\ and \PD\ separately.
CreativityPrism \citep{hou_creativityprism_2025} and LitBench \citep{fein_litbench_2025} provide partial coverage but neither conditions scores on an explicit \TR.
A concrete next step is a claim-level annotation layer with labels such as supported, hallucination, productive divergence, unverifiable, and stylistic variation.
Such a layer should be evaluated as an open research problem, including whether it changes model rankings or instead primarily improves error diagnosis.


\section{Discussion}\label{sec:discussion_conclusion}

% === CLAIMS SUPPORTED HERE ===
% Synthesizes Claims 3--6; clarifies scope and responsible impact.

\subsection{Implications for evaluation practice}

The practical consequence of \TR-relative evaluation is a shift from defect counting to \emph{regime-conditioned diagnosis}.
Rather than asking ``how much does the output hallucinate?'', evaluation should ask ``does its divergence exceed what the \TR\ licenses?''
Three verdicts result: \emph{aligned} (divergence matches \TR), \textit{excessive-}\textbf{\Hallu} (unsupported claims where grounding is required), or \textit{insufficient-}\textbf{\PD} (output too conservative for a permissive \TR).
Because writing format alone shifts measured hallucination by over 20~\% (Table~\ref{tab:key-findings}), regime-specific baselines are essential: identical rates carry different meanings under strict and permissive contracts.
At the same time, evaluation under permissive regimes should still flag \emph{truth-commitment violations}---instances where the model presents invented content as factual rather than as hypothesis or creative proposal \citep{bang_hallulens_2025, hou_creativityprism_2025}.

\subsection{What drives measured hallucination}\label{sec:discussion}

Three findings refine the picture of what actually drives measured \Hallu.

\paragraph{The prompt is part of the hallucination.}
Prompt-level variance is substantial (intraclass correlation coefficient (ICC) = 0.65): the same model at the same temperature exhibits markedly different \Hallu\ rates depending on prompt content and structure.
\Hallu\ is therefore not purely a model deficiency; prompt engineering matters as much as model selection, and benchmarks should sample prompts diversely enough to capture this variance.

\paragraph{Temperature is not the main control knob.}
We find no meaningful association between temperature and \Hallu\ ($r = -0.006$, $p = 0.52$), a null result robust across correlation methods, GLM, and mixed models.
This aligns with recent evidence that temperature is a weak \CI\ parameter \citep{du_optimizing_2025, peeperkorn_is_2024}: semantic-level signals in the prompt appear to dominate token-level sampling noise.

\paragraph{Format-level factual constraints moderate the creativity effect.}
The interaction between \CI\ level and task type is significant (OR = 0.77 for \textsc{very\_creative} $\times$ \textsc{news\_article}): when a writing format carries strong factual expectations, creative prompting has a weaker effect on \Hallu, suggesting the model partially internalizes those constraints.
This mirrors the layer-wise \CI/\Hallu\ trade-offs reported by \citet{he_shakespearean_2025}, though our evidence arises from prompt-level manipulations rather than model-internal dynamics.
Together, these three patterns reinforce recent critiques of task-agnostic evaluation \citep{bang_hallulens_2025, wang_user-centric_2024, cyriac_metrics_2025} and identify prompt content, not sampling temperature, as the first-order confound that benchmarks must control.

\subsection{Limitations}\label{sec:limitations}

Several design choices bound the scope of our study without undermining its diagnostic role.

\paragraph{Binary verification.}
Our claim-level pipeline uses \texttt{supported}/\texttt{hallucinated} verdicts, following the state-of-the-art HalluLens protocol \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}, and omits an ``unverifiable'' category.
Accordingly, absolute rates should be interpreted as strict-regime unsupportedness estimates, not as full \TR-aware judgments.
This may overestimate absolute hallucination rates under creative conditions, where invented but unfalsifiable content is common; however, because the same classification applies uniformly across all conditions, the \emph{relative} comparisons that motivate our claims (effect of \CI, task type, and their interaction) remain informative.
Permissive regimes require additional labels such as \PD, unverifiable content, and non-truth-conditional stylistic variation.

\paragraph{Knowledge-base scope.}
Wikipedia serves as the verification oracle, which is standard practice in factuality evaluation \citep{thorne_fever_2018, lin_truthfulqa_2022}.
In this study, Wikipedia is fixed by the HalluLens-style verification protocol and is appropriate for the general-knowledge prompts we evaluate; it should not be interpreted as a universal oracle.
In a \TR-aware benchmark, $O$ should be explicitly annotated and selected according to the task domain, for example source documents, domain-specific corpora, recent-event databases, or user-provided context.

\paragraph{Format-oracle mismatch.}
The \textsc{lesson\_plan} effect should not be read only as weaker factual discipline.
Lesson plans naturally introduce objectives, activities, assessment criteria, and classroom scaffolding that are pedagogically useful but not always Wikipedia-groundable.
The high measured hallucination rate for this format may therefore combine genre norms, structural-template demands, genuine unsupported factual claims, and oracle coverage limits.

\paragraph{Prompt and \TR\ alignment.}
Some prompts in our design are ambiguous with respect to the intended truth regime: open-ended formulations can make it difficult to determine whether a given deviation is \TR-licensed or not.
Extending the task gradient to genres with sharper regime boundaries (e.g., fiction vs.\ legal analysis) and annotating each prompt with an explicit $(O, \sigma, \kappa)$ contract would strengthen future replications.

\paragraph{Permissive-regime diagnostic.}
We also ran an indicative $\kappa$ HIGH/LOW diagnostic to probe what happens when invention is explicitly licensed.
We keep it out of the main empirical claims because it is a diagnostic rerun, not a full permissive-regime benchmark.
Its role is to illustrate the limitation motivating this paper: a binary verifier has no \PD\ label, so it can map licensed invention to hallucination rather than distinguishing productive divergence from truth-regime violation.
Appendix~\ref{app:kappa-diagnostic} reports the concrete values.

\section{Conclusion}\label{sec:conclusion}

This paper argues that hallucination is not a binary property of text but a violation relative to a prompt's truth regime.
The vocabulary introduced here, $\TR(p)=(O,\sigma,\kappa)$ together with \CI, \PD, and \Hallu, makes explicit what current hallucination and creativity evaluations often leave implicit: which oracle governs truth, which stylistic deviations are allowed, and whether new truth-conditional content is licensed.
Our strict-regime study does not solve \TR-aware evaluation.
It shows why such evaluation is needed: even a strong HalluLens-style binary verifier reports substantially different hallucination rates as prompt format and creative intent change, despite a fixed low-$\kappa$ contract.
The research agenda is therefore to move from defect counting to regime-conditioned diagnosis, so that evaluation can penalize harmful fabrication under strict regimes while preserving productive divergence where exploration is intended.

