\end{table*}

\noindent Hallucination rate correlates with TTCT
(divergent thinking, $\rho = 0.23$) and with the creativity composite ($\rho = 0.17$), while the correlation with TTCW (writing quality) is negligible ($\rho \approx 0$).
This pattern is consistent with the $\sigma$/$\kappa$ distinction: stylistic latitude ($\sigma$) alone increases measured divergence from factual baselines, even when the prompt never licenses factual invention ($\kappa$ low).


%% ================================================================
%%  APPENDIX B — Experimental Details
%% ================================================================
\section{Experimental Details}\label{app:details}

\subsection{Formal Claim-Level Decision Rule}\label{app:decision-rule}

Given prompt $p$ and output $y$:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Infer or specify the regime $\TR(p)$: what is truth-conditional, what is evidence-bound, what is optionally speculative, and what (if anything) may be invented \citep{bang_hallulens_2025, huang_survey_2025}.
    \item Decompose $y$ into atomic claims at the chosen granularity (ideally claim-level) \citep{huang_survey_2025, ji_survey_2023}.
    \item For each claim $c$:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item if $c$ is truth-conditional under $\TR(p)$ and unsupported/incorrect relative to the oracle, label it \Hallu\ \citep{ji_survey_2023, huang_survey_2025};
        \item else if $c$ is permitted under $\TR(p)$ and improves usefulness/appropriateness while remaining constraint-compliant, label it \PD\ \citep{acar_creativity_2019, runco_standard_2012};
        \item else label it \emph{neither} (e.g., purely stylistic variation or benign noise).
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Prompt Template Structure}\label{app:prompt-template}

See Appendix~\ref{app:lego} for full block definitions.
An \texttt{AblationConfig} dataclass allows toggling each block independently,
enabling future ablation studies.

\noindent This modular design ensures full factorial crossing:
$3~\text{tasks} \times 3~\text{creativity levels} \times 3~\text{lengths}
\times k~\text{subjects} = 1{,}389$~unique prompts.

\subsection{FactHalu Verification Pipeline}\label{app:pipeline}

The claim-level verification pipeline follows the HalluLens evaluation
paradigm \citep{bang_hallulens_2025} and proceeds in four stages:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Abstention filter.}
    An LLM judges whether the generated text constitutes a genuine attempt
    at the task or an explicit refusal/hedge.
    Abstained outputs are excluded from analysis.

    \item \textbf{Claim extraction.}
    A prompted LLM extracts atomic, independently verifiable claims from
    each sentence.
    Context is provided via a sliding window with \texttt{<SOS>}/\texttt{<EOS>}
    markers to preserve discourse-level meaning.

    \item \textbf{Evidence retrieval.}
    For each extracted claim, we perform hybrid retrieval against the
    English Wikipedia (April~2023 dump):
    BM25 (lexical) and dense retrieval (\texttt{gtr-t5-large} encoder).
    The top-5 passages per claim are concatenated as evidence context.

    \item \textbf{NLI verdict.}
    A verifier LLM issues a binary verdict (\texttt{supported} or
    \texttt{hallucinated}) given the claim, the evidence passages, and
    the original generation context.
    The primary evaluator for all three LLM stages is
    \textbf{mimo-v2-flash} \cite{xiaomi2026mimov2flash}.

    To assess evaluator reliability, we replicate the full pipeline on 90 shared prompts ($n = 1{,}943$ claims) with four different evaluator LLMs: mimo-v2-flash \cite{xiaomi2026mimov2flash}, 
    deepseek-v3.2 \cite{deepseek2025v32}, 
    llama-3.3-70b-instruct \cite{meta2024llama33}, 
    and qwen3.5-397b-a17b \cite{alibaba2025qwen3}.
\end{enumerate}

\noindent\textbf{Prompt-level aggregation.}
We compute \texttt{hallucination\_rate} $= n_{\text{hallucinated}} / n_{\text{verified}}$
at the prompt level, excluding \texttt{no\_claim} rows.
The binary scheme (no ``unverifiable'' category) likely overestimates absolute
rates but preserves relative ordering across conditions
(Section~\ref{sec:limitations}).

\subsection{Run Coverage Summary}

The study comprises 53 experimental runs spanning 10 models across five providers: deepseek-v3.2 \cite{deepseek2025v32},  gemini-3-flash-preview \cite{google2025gemini3flash},  gemma-3-27b-it \cite{google2025gemma3}, gpt-5.2 \cite{openai2025gpt52,openai2025gpt52systemcard},  grok-3-mini \cite{xai2025grok3mini},  grok-4.1-fast \cite{xai2025grok41fast},  mistral-small-creative \cite{mistral2025smallcreative}, nemotron-nano-12b-v2-vl \cite{nvidia2025nemotron},  and qwen3-30b-a3b-instruct-2507 \cite{alibaba2025qwen3}, with temperature $\in \{0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0\}$ and 3 target lengths.
CreativityPrism scoring is available for 29 complete runs ($N = 8{,}376$);
the remaining 24 runs lack creativity annotations due to pipeline coverage gaps.
Table~\ref{tab:supp-run-coverage} summarizes coverage by model.

\begin{table}[h]
    \centering
    \caption{Run coverage by model (53 total runs; 29 with creativity scores).}
    \label{tab:supp-run-coverage}
    \small
    \begin{tabular}{l c c}
        \toprule
        \textbf{Model} & \textbf{Total runs} & \textbf{w/ creativity} \\
        \midrule
        grok-3-mini & 13 & 12 \\
        gemini-3-flash-preview & 10 & 2 \\
        deepseek-v3.2 & 3 & 3 \\
        gemma-3-27b-it & 3 & 3 \\
        gpt-5.2 & 6 & 0 \\
        grok-4.1-fast & 6 & 1 \\
        mistral-small-creative & 3 & 3 \\
