        qwen3-30b-a3b-instruct & 6 & 2 \\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Statistical Analysis}\label{app:stats-methods}

To ensure our findings are robust, we use several statistical methods.
First, we use logistic regression (a binomial GLM with a logit link) to measure how much each factor (task, creativity, length) multiplies the odds of a hallucination occurring (reported as Odds Ratios, OR) \citep{nelder_generalized_1972, hosmer2013applied}.
Second, we use a generalized linear mixed model (GLMM) to calculate how much of the hallucination rate is driven by the specific prompt topic itself, rather than our experimental settings \citep{breslow_clayton_1993, bates_lme4_2015}.
Third, we use mediation analysis to verify that creative prompts cause hallucinations directly, rather than simply causing the model to write more claims \citep{baron_kenny_1986, imai_keele_tingley_2010}.
Finally, to prevent false positives from running multiple tests, all $p$-values are adjusted using FDR correction \citep{benjamini_controlling_1995, benjamini_yekutieli_2001}, and correlations are verified through 5{,}000 bootstrap iterations \citep{efron_tibshirani_1993}.

