\ref{lengthlegend}
\caption{Median hallucination rate by model, task, and requested length.
    Each panel shows one task; lines connect the same model across output lengths.
    Longer outputs show moderately higher hallucination rates, but the effect is much weaker than that of task type or creativity level.
    Verification follows HalluLens \citep{bang_hallulens_2025}.}
\label{fig:length-effect}
\end{figure*}

\paragraph{Reading Figure~\ref{fig:length-effect}.}
The length effect is visible but modest.
In the \textsc{interview} panel (left), most models show a gentle upward trend from 250 to 1{,}000~words, with the exception of \texttt{deepseek-v3.2} (blue), which remains nearly flat.
The \textsc{lesson\_plan} panel (middle) is again the highest overall, but slopes are compressed: models that already hallucinate heavily at 250~words have little room to increase further (a possible ceiling effect).
In the \textsc{news\_article} panel (right), some models (e.g., \texttt{grok-4.1-fast}, green) show a steeper rise, while others remain stable.
Overall, the length effect ($\rho = 0.11$) is roughly one-third the magnitude of the creativity effect ($\rho = 0.30$) and one-quarter of the task effect ($\rho = 0.45$), reinforcing that \emph{what} the model is asked to do matters far more than \emph{how long} it writes.

