%% ================================================================
%%  APPENDIX G — Indicative Kappa HIGH/LOW Diagnostic
%% ================================================================
\section{Indicative \texorpdfstring{$\kappa$}{kappa} HIGH/LOW Diagnostic}\label{app:kappa-diagnostic}

The main experiment intentionally holds $\kappa$ low: factual invention is not licensed, so unsupported truth-conditional claims are violations under the tested regime.
To probe the failure mode reviewers identified, we also ran an indicative matched diagnostic with an explicit invention-license block in the prompt generator.
Under $\kappa$ LOW, factual invention is disallowed.
Under $\kappa$ HIGH, fictional, speculative, or illustrative additions are permitted when useful, provided they are not presented as verified facts.

Across 7 runs, 360 prompts, and 214K claim rows, the HalluLens-style binary verifier reports higher measured hallucination under $\kappa$ HIGH than under $\kappa$ LOW: the paired HIGH--LOW difference is +5.1 percentage points, the GLM odds ratio for LOW vs.\ HIGH is 0.76, and the mixed-model coefficient for LOW is $-0.053$.
We do not interpret these values as evidence that permissive prompts are worse.
They are diagnostic evidence that the binary supported/hallucinated pipeline lacks a \PD\ label: when invention is licensed by the prompt, licensed unsupported content can still be counted as hallucination.
For this reason, the rerun supports the research agenda rather than replacing it with a completed permissive-regime benchmark.

%% ================================================================
%%  APPENDIX H — Prompt Lego Blocks: Full Definitions
%% ================================================================
\section{Prompt Lego Blocks: Full Block Definitions}\label{app:lego}

All blocks are defined in \texttt{utils/prompt\_lego\_blocks.py}.
The module is structured as six independent components (A--F) that
\texttt{STATIC\_USER\_PROMPT\_TEMPLATE} assembles deterministically.

\subsection{Block A --- Creativity Style (\texttt{CREATIVITY\_STYLE})}

\begin{description}
    \item[\textsc{factual}]
    ``Tone: neutral, informative, straightforward.
    Avoid metaphors, theatrics, and flowery language.
    Focus on clarity and precision.''

    \item[\textsc{hybrid}]
    ``Tone: clear and engaging with light creative flourishes
    (rhythm, mild imagery, occasional vivid word choice),
    staying focused on the topic.
    Balance accessibility with style.''

    \item[\textsc{very\_creative}]
    ``Tone: highly stylized and distinctive (strong voice, playful constraints,
    vivid imagery, unexpected angles), but still centered on the topic.
    The form itself becomes part of the content.''
\end{description}

\subsection{Block B --- Task Constraints (\texttt{TASK\_CONSTRAINTS}), Subset Used}

\paragraph{\textsc{interview}}
\textit{Use-case: Q\&A for a community newsletter; accessible, skimmable.}
\begin{itemize}\setlength{\itemsep}{0pt}
    \item Exactly 8 Q/A pairs; markers \texttt{Q1:/A1:} \ldots{} \texttt{Q8:/A8:}.
    \item Answers: 2--4 sentences each.
    \item Questions progress from basic to nuanced.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{\textsc{news\_article}}
\textit{Use-case: news-style explainer for a general audience on deadline.}
\begin{itemize}\setlength{\itemsep}{0pt}
    \item Headline (one line, compelling).
    \item Deck: exactly 2 sentences.
    \item 3 sections with clear subheadings.
    \item Exactly 2 direct quotes in double quotes (attributed to named sources).
    \item 1 forward-looking perspective sentence at the end.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{\textsc{lesson\_plan}}
\textit{Use-case: teacher lesson plan for a class.}
\begin{itemize}\setlength{\itemsep}{0pt}
    \item Grade level specified at top.
    \item Learning objectives: exactly 3.
    \item Materials needed: list format.
    \item 1 activity with time allocations.
    \item Assessment criteria section.
\end{itemize}

\noindent Task constraints are \emph{identical across all creativity levels}:
Block~A (style) and Block~B (format) are orthogonal by design.
The full \texttt{TaskName} enum lists 16 task types; only these 3 are used
in our study.

\subsection{Block C --- Length (\texttt{LENGTH\_BLOCK})}

\begin{quote}\small
\texttt{Target length: \{length\_words\} words (plus or minus 15\%).}
\end{quote}

\noindent We use $\lambda \in \{250, 500, 1{,}000\}$.

\subsection{Block D --- Banned Phrases (\texttt{BANNED\_PHRASES})}

The following 19 terms are forbidden in generated outputs to prevent
benchmark contamination and suppress LLM meta-commentary about its own
uncertainty:

\begin{quote}\footnotesize
\textit{wikipedia, wikidata, benchmark, evaluation, oracle, rag, retrieval,
closed-book, hallucination, ground truth, cite sources, citations required,
as an ai, system prompt, language model, trained on, knowledge cutoff,
i don't have access, i cannot browse.}
\end{quote}

\subsection{Blocks E--F --- Prompt Schemas and Final Template}

Block~E (\texttt{BLUEPRINT\_SCHEMA}) and Block~F (\texttt{FINAL\_PROMPT\_SCHEMA})
support a two-stage LLM generation path (blueprint JSON $\to$ naturalized user
message).
For reproducibility, all 1{,}389 prompts use the deterministic
\texttt{STATIC\_USER\_PROMPT\_TEMPLATE} instead, whose \textsc{Output Rules}
block encodes the strict $\TR$ at every creativity level:

\begin{quote}\small\itshape
``If you're unsure about a specific detail, keep it high-level or phrase it
cautiously rather than guessing.''
\end{quote}

\noindent Together with \texttt{BANNED\_PHRASES}, this instruction prevents models
from filling knowledge gaps with confidently stated inventions, bounding the
confounding between $\sigma$ (style latitude) and $\kappa$ (invention license).

